President Uhuru Kenyatta began his second term in office by holding talks with South Sudan President Salva Kiir and a special envoy of Chinese President Xi Jinping. The President began by meeting Wang Jiarui who represented Jinping at the swearing-in ceremony at Kasarani stadium on Tuesday. China is currently Kenya’s biggest trading partner and a major investor, with interests ranging from construction to apparels and technology. More on this: Enter the Dragon: Kenya-China relations Also read: SGR phase two to grow Kenya, China trade gap The special envoy delivered the message that his country will continue supporting Kenya’s development. “My visit signifies the republic of China and the Communist Party of China’s support for Kenya and your government." Jiarui is expected to tour the Standard Gauge Railway, one of the flagship projects accomplished through China and Kenya's cooperation. Uhuru thanked the people and government of China for their strong support for Kenya. In May, China elevated its bilateral relationship with Kenya to one of strategic cooperation and Chinese leaders pledged to see the country grow. Uhuru later held talks with Kiir who was among 11 heads of state who visited Kenya for the ceremony. Kenya has played a leading role in efforts to find a lasting solution for peace in South Sudan.  South Sudan President Salva Kiir with President Uhuru Kenyatta at State House in Nairobi during their meeting on November 29, 2017. /PSCU Africa integration, especially practical steps that make integration functional, and International trade are key planks of the vision Uhuru outlined in his address to the nation after being sworn-in. More on this: [Statement] Uhuru details plans for last five years as President  The President also held talks with Firmin Ayessa, deputy prime minister of Congo-Brazaville, who delivered a special message from President Sassou Ngueso. Click here for the latest political news